00:45:16.479 --> 00:45:22.479
What we've got now is a process that says we'll take a certain version of R, a certain set of

00:45:22.479 --> 00:45:28.479
packages and a certain versions of those packages. We build it,

00:45:28.479 --> 00:45:34.479
we test it, we document it and then it goes under change control so that there are no sudden

00:45:34.479 --> 00:45:40.479
changes to that instance of R. And it's the same, it's getting easier now because we've got

00:45:40.479 --> 00:45:46.479
containers for that. So we can test and validate and qualify and document the container

00:45:46.479 --> 00:45:52.479
and then deploy it in various places. What that then means is that as far as

00:45:52.479 --> 00:45:58.479
no one can get in and install packages in that environment unless

00:45:58.479 --> 00:46:04.479
it goes back through that whole process. So that kind of then takes that wild west away

00:46:04.479 --> 00:46:10.479
in that framework. And I'm also militant about

00:46:10.479 --> 00:46:16.479
telling my colleagues not to run anything in production on their desktop for the reasons that we discussed earlier

00:46:16.479 --> 00:46:22.479
that I can't tell what they've got and I can't tell what state it's in.

00:46:22.479 --> 00:46:28.479
So with those two messages, I'm kind of saying, well, look, anything that's on production needs to come from

00:46:28.479 --> 00:46:34.479
here. You can do what you like on your desktop, but if you then try and run it

00:46:34.479 --> 00:46:40.479
over here, you can't come and tell me, oh, I need to get this package in there

00:46:40.479 --> 00:46:46.479
and I need it by tomorrow morning. Because the answer is, well, it needs to go through that whole cycle

00:46:46.479 --> 00:46:52.479
in order to have the confidence that this snapshot version here is still valid.

00:46:52.479 --> 00:46:58.479
My personal view is that if you lock down something too much,

00:46:58.479 --> 00:47:04.479
people will find workarounds. So if you get told you cannot use open source,

00:47:04.479 --> 00:47:10.479
you must use this set of products, if that person wants to, they'll find a way

00:47:10.479 --> 00:47:16.479
to get around that and to sort it out. So if this way of doing things, the official way,

00:47:16.479 --> 00:47:22.479
the good way of doing things is easy, then

00:47:22.479 --> 00:47:28.479
hopefully people will do that than this nasty workaround over here.

00:47:28.479 --> 00:47:34.479
I like that. Make the good way of doing things easy.

